_0.Value: Besides PowerShell script files (.ps1), there are other file types that might have the same syntax or be related to PowerShell modules. These include:

_2.Value: PowerShell module files (.psm1) - These are files that contain a collection of functions, variables, aliases, and other resources that can be imported and used as a module. They can also export some or all of their members to make them available to other scripts or modules. You can learn more about PowerShell module files here: How to Write a PowerShell Script Module - PowerShell

_4.Value: PowerShell data files (.psd1) - These are files that store configuration data or serve as module manifest files. A module manifest file describes the contents and properties of a module, such as its name, version, author, dependencies, and exported members. You can learn more about PowerShell data files and module manifest files here: How to Write a PowerShell Module Manifest - PowerShell

_6.Value: PowerShell XML files (.ps1xml) - These are files that define the formatting and type extensions for objects in PowerShell. They can also serve as the help file for a module, if they have a specific name and location. You can learn more about PowerShell XML files here: about_Types.ps1xml - PowerShell and about_Format.ps1xml - PowerShell

_8.Value: PowerShell session configuration files (.pssc) - These are files that define the environment and capabilities of sessions that use a specific session configuration or endpoint. They can be used to create custom session configurations without using complex C# assemblies or scripts. You can learn more about PowerShell session configuration files here: about_Session_Configuration_Files - PowerShell
